title: [SegaNet] Shi no Meikyuu - Labyrinth of Death (Japan)
description: Labyrinth of Death is literally that, a labyrinth filled with monsters whose only objective is to kill you. Your character starts off in a rectangular room with no visible exit. Your objective is to make it out of the labyrinth (that you are inexplicably trapped in) alive! Although the games text is exclusively in Japanese, it is still a fairly simple game to understand. You move around from room to room making your way to a staircase that will lead you to the next room and eventually, to an exit out of the labyrinth. You have to move your character to the edge of a room to find out whats beyond the edge, whether that be a wall or a path out of that room. Your "map" of the floor slowly reveals itself as you unlock the next part of the path, in a style reminiscent of the pokemon mystery dungeon series. If you get stuck facing a monster that you just can't harm, then you can easily pick up on of the numerous weapons/armor/helmets/magic staff/etc. that are litter the dungeon floors. Overall, I would definitely recommend this game to anyone who is interested in finding out where the mystery dungeon games got their root. Also, I would like to add that this game (visually) felt like a game that Finn and Jake would play on BMO in Adventure Time.

Characters can also be powered up throughout the game. Some changes have also been made to the field, such as glass walls surrounding most of the walls, making it very difficult to send the ball flying out of the field. The game was released in Japan for the Sega Mega Drive on the fourth of March 1994. The game had prior to that been released as an Arcade game, on the NeoGeo, NeoGeo CD, and Super Nintendo Entertainment System. It was developed by Pallas and the the Japanese Sega Mega Drive version was published by Electronic Arts. The game utilizes a password system for keeping track of progress.

title: Master of Monsters (USA)
description:
If you are looking for a 'Diamond among coals' in strategy games, then this game will make you satisfied.  Based on a Hexagon grid, You basicly control a Master, that in turn controls monsters and magic.The game consists of you taking turns against either computer or player enemies summoning monsters used to destroy the opponent(s). You start yout turn with some magic regained, and that magis is used to summon different kind of monsters and use spells that can help your monsters or harm your opponents. Across the map are towers that you can take over by placing one of your monsters on to increase your cap on the number of monsters you can summon, but remember that your opponents can do the same. Monsters can fight by being adjacent to the enemy, either with a range or melee attack, and the opponent counters the same, if they dont die by your hit first. As monsters fight and destroy other monsters, they gain experience, which after so much is gained, they level up and evolve into stronger monsters. During the campain run, all of your monsters that survived the level with you will continue onto the next one, meaning if you have the level 4 King Dragon, it will help you anialate anything on the next round and so on.
So many people overlook this game simply becasue it was on the Sega Genesis and got very little fame due to it being almost a soly Japanese game, but belive me whn I say this: More strategy games need to be based like this one. you won't regret trying Master of Monsters out. I still regret selling it.

title: Megaman - The Wily Wars (Europe)
description:
Mega Man the Wily Wars is a game that was only released in Europe and Japan. That's why you hardly (if ever) heard of it.The game is nothing short of great. Has (obviously) graphics that are a lot more detailed, coloful and nitid than the NES originals. While not one of the best sounding games in the console, the FM instruments do the job quite well.
MMWW utilizes a save feature to keep the progress you make on all three games instead of using passwords.
So what makes it great, if it's just a remake?
The fact that it features a fourth hidden game you unlock when you beat the first three. In it, you can choose ANY combination of both weapons and items you desire from the three games! It also has bosses based off the "Journey to the West" tale (same as Goku from DBZ), plus another 4 new ones, some neat visual effects...
Worth mentioning as well is that the Wily Tower's level 1 is based on MM1 enemies and art, the second based off MM2, etc.
Ah, and for the other reviewer, here: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oN9-rrfOdRM&feature=player_detailpage#t=501s
 
You don't have to be a huge fan of the Blue Bomber to enjoy this one. Definitely give it a go! And watch which rom dump you get - otherwise the game won't save your progress.
